Evangeline has all the charm of a hole in the wall with good, simple, cajun food. To my surprise it was quiiiiiiet on a Sunday night, but that could be due to covid. Staff were professional and accommodating. I actually have nothing negative to say about the restaurant. It was quiet, had that fancy but not snobby rough brick, dimly lit interior and *felt* expensive despite its moderate prices. I really enjoyed that they had bar space, dining space, and a deceptively large outdoor space. It just wasn't... special? There was no mood in the place. No firm culture. It felt like a run of the mill joint. I enjoyed it but it was missing something I can't quite put my finger on. Maybe it was the lack of energy that I expected to see and didn't from the customers. No complaints though, not real ones anyway. Enjoy your time there!

Great food, great atmosphere, and great employees! My husband and I stopped here on our first night in New Orleans (our first stop altogether) to grab a drink and get our bearings. We ended up staying for 2 hours, drinking, having a quick bite to eat, and chatting with Brent (the awesome bartender) and some of the friendly servers. They have a good happy hour from 3-6 with drink specials and snacks/small plates. We had the catfish tacos and the nachos (which were awesome!). The nachos were on Zapp’s chips instead of tortilla chips, with cheese sauce, pulled pork bbq, jalapeños, etc. YUMMY!! I recommend checking them out!!

Great place for drinks or dinner! We stopped in for the happy hour (3-6) for a drink but then ordered the Cajun Nachos (awesome twist on Zapp’s Chips), catfish tacos (I usually really don’t like catfish, but these were amazing!) and, of course, a cup of gumbo (excellent). All that to say, we actually stayed longer because of the awesome service. We had a great time getting Nola advice from Brent and the crew (we’d only been in town for 3 hours). I made a reservation for a party of 25 about 6 weeks ago for our bachelor/bachelorette party - it ended up being 18 people and I communicated that to the event manager a week prior to the event.  First, a no point did the event manager tell me that seating would be outside.  It's HOT in August.  If I had known it was outside, I would have made reservations elsewhere.  Where would we have been seated if it had rained?!  Secondly, it took almost hour just to get water.  Third, the server spilled hot gumbo on one of my guests and didn't even apologize.  Fourth, I ate my appetizer but had to cancel my meal because I was so overheated.  Fifth, at the two-hour mark, many of our guests still hadn't been served and most of the food that had been served was cold - they also brought food to the table that wasn't even ordered.  It was a total train wreck.  Luckily, some people in my party spoke with management and they took care of it (thank you for that).  The few people who were served hot food did say the food was very good so that's the reason for anything other than one star.  As I was leaving, someone did apologize to me directly and I appreciated that.  She was very kind.  Some of my guests drove over 500 miles to get there and I was more sad than mad at the situation.  A word of advice: If you aren't able to comfortably and efficiently accommodate the number of customers who are requesting service, please be honest and convey that. There is no absolutely shame in turning someone away if the venue isn't large enough to host that many people.

I’m not exaggerating when I say I had one of, if not THE best meal of my life here. My sister and I stopped in after a ghost tour of the city and sat at the bar, where the bartender (don’t remember his name but he had long hair pulled back) made us feel right at home.  We ordered the gumbo, jambalaya, red beans and rice, and fried okra, and topped it all off with the bread pudding beignets. The food was piping hot, perfectly flavorful, and really hit the spot. We couldn’t stop taking turns telling each other how happy we were. Hands down the best place for real creole/Cajun food and friendly service. Will absolutely be back before our trip is over.
Great place for dinner or dessert. Try the bread pudding benignets.

Love the place. Food was delicious, for reasonable price.

This restaurant has quickly become one of my favorites in New Orleans. The atmosphere is great, and they have a nice little outdoor patio area as well. It was too cold to sit out there when I went, but I imagine on a nice day it is simply lovely.  Well there, there was some live music, and while we sat basically right next to the bassist and pianist, they continued to check and make sure they were not playing too loudly for us to hold conversation. They were very considerate. The music was not annoyingly fast, but rather reminded me of a very cool hip jazz club. Again there were only two instruments in the group, so that probably helped.  The food was exceptional. I really really enjoyed each and every bite of each meal I tried... I only had the meal pictured, but I tried to others and they were incredible. Dessert was also on point. I only had a draft beer, so I cannot attest to their mixed beverages, but the bar seemed well stocked and well manned. Our waitress (Denise) was very attentive and made wonderful serving suggestions.  The portions were just right to fill you up but not make you feel bloated. We ended up feeling a little bloated because we could not resist trying an appetizer (fried alligator... Very tasty) and a dessert (Bread pudding... Also very tasty)! But even then, it wasn't uncomfortably full...  The prices were very reasonable... It was about $40 per person (before tip) . That included three adult males sharing an appetizer, each person having a main course, sharing a dessert and two adult beverages/one iced tea.  I had no idea that this restaurant was on some stupid Food Network Channel show, but that would not have caused me to go here in the first place. Look at the photos of their food!  I am glad that we tried this place and I am absolutely certain to return on a future visit to New Orleans.

The waitstaff were attentive and quick and let us know happy hour was going on so $3 for a selection of draft beers was awesome. Myself and my husband ordered the gator creole style which had a bit of a peppery kick to it and was delicious. I ordered the Acadia crawfish grits and it was to die for. They had run out of jambalaya so I ordered red beans and rice. The portion was appropriate and everything tasted fine. I finished my meal, paid, and the group still had not arrived to sit at the first table.  After eating, I had some indigestion...which was surprising to me, since it was flavorful but not spicy and unfried.  I hope that they had not served me something that was going bad ... I loved the crab cakes and wanted to order more for myself. Good thing I didn't because the entree was amazing.  I ordered the jambalaya. Spice level was good for a good kick that just lingers in your mouth and the seafood was fresh. The rest of my group was happy with their meals as well.
